<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Calamagrostis muiriana </i>is a perennial bunchgrass. Old plants spread outward while dying in the middle, forming rings. Leaves are glaucous, narrow, and roll up when wilted. Culms are < 15 cm long with short panicles of spreading spikelets (Wilson and Gray 2002). <br/>
<br/>
Botanists used the name <i>C. breweri </i>for plants in the Sierra Nevada until Wilson and Gray (2002) differentiated plants that grow south of Carson Pass in the central Sierra Nevada as <i>C. muiriana. </i>Those plants differ in morphology, isozyme patterns, chromosome number, and ecology from <i>C. breweri </i>that grows in the northern Sierra Nevada, Klamath Mountains, and Oregon. Unlike <i>C. muiriana, </i>the northern plants are not community dominants. Building on the early descriptions of the alliance (Ratliff 1982, 1985), we have restricted the alliance to the central and southern Sierra Nevada. Stands with high cover of <i>Vaccinium cespitosum </i>are in the <i>Vaccinium cespitosum </i>alliance. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
